			<!-- OTHER APPS BY YOU -->
			<div class="wow fadeInUp content-card" style="margin-top: 10;">
      	<span class="text-subtitle" style="font-size: 2em; font-weight: 300; color: #333">Research</span><br>
				<span class="text-description" style="font-size: 1.1em">
					<i>From polytopes...</i><br>
					A polytope is the convex hull of a finite set of points in an euclidian space $R^d$, for instance a triangle is a 2-dimensional polytope. These objects appear in a wide range of mathematical works, both in theoretical and applied contexts. In particular in discrete geometry and linear programing, as the feasible solutions domain of a linear program is a polytope. And solve a linear program with the simplex algorithm consists in running a walk on a graph of a polytope. A class of polytopes of special interest I study is that of <i>lattice (d,k)-polytopes</i>. These polytopes are contained in the hypercube $[0,k]^d$, where <i>k</i> is a positive integer, and their vertices have integer coordinates. Despite the fact that those objects are very common, their combinatorics are still not well understood when the dimension rises. Characterization in dimension higher than 3 is a complete mystery.
					<br>
					<i>...To random sampling</i><br>
					A random sampler for combinatorial objects is an algorithm that generates a random object following a desired distribution. Most of the time we use the uniform distribution over the objects with a same size. A random sampler, not only allows to have experimental results, but also enables to test conjectures on the sampled objects. Another purpose is the study of the effectivness of algorithms taking them as inputs. Then in order to better understand the lattice <i>(d,k)</i>-polytopes, the purpose of my works is to build an effective random sampler for them. There exists many generic technics but currently I am working on a random sampler get from a Markov chain.
      </div>

